{{for|other people called John Thomson Mason|John Thomson Mason (disambiguation)}} {{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}} {{Infobox Congressman | name =John Thomson Mason Jr. | image name = | birth_date={{birth date|1815|05|09}} | birth_place =[[Montpelier (Clear Spring, Maryland)|Montpelier]], [[Clear Spring, Maryland|Clear Spring]], Maryland | death_date={{death date and age|1873|03|28|1815|05|09}} | death_place =[[Elkton, Maryland|Elkton]], Maryland | state = [[Maryland]] | district = [[Maryland's 6th congressional district|6th]] | term_start =March 4, 1841 | term_end = March 3, 1843 | preceded = [[Francis Thomas]] | succeeded = [[Thomas Ara Spence]] | order2 = 24th [[Secretary of State of Maryland]] | term_start2 = 1872 | term_end2 = 1873 | governor2 = [[William Pinkney Whyte]] | predecessor2 = [[Richard C. Hollyday]] | successor2 = [[Richard C. Hollyday]] | office3 = Member of [[Maryland House of Delegates]] | term3 = 1838&ndash;1839 | party =[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] | spouse = Margaret Augusta Cowan | occupation = Attorney | alma_mater= [[Princeton University]] | residence= [[Stafford Hall]], [[Washington County, Maryland|Washington County]], Maryland | children=4 }} '''John Thomson Mason Jr.''' (May 9, 1815 – March 28, 1873)<ref name=GH>{{cite web | url=http://gunstonhall.com/masonweb/p8.htm#i365 | title=John Thomson Mason Jr. | accessdate=March 7, 2009 | publisher=Gunston Hall | author=Gunston Hall}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=PG>{{cite web | url=http://politicalgraveyard.com/families/10855.html | title=Mason family of Virginia | date= June 16, 2008| accessdate=March 7, 2009 | publisher=The Political Graveyard | author=The Political Graveyard}}</ref> was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Congressman]] from [[Maryland]], representing the [[United States House of Representatives, Maryland District 6|sixth district]] from 1841 to 1843.<ref name=PG/>
==Early life and education== Born at the [[Montpelier (Clear Spring, Maryland)|Montpelier]] estate near [[Hagerstown, Maryland]], Mason was educated by a private tutor and graduated from [[Princeton College]] in 1836. He studied law, was admitted to the bar, and commenced practice in Hagerstown in 1838.
==Political career== Mason later served as a member of the [[Maryland House of Delegates]] in 1838 and 1839, and was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the [[27th United States Congress|Twenty-seventh Congress]], serving one term from March 4, 1841 to March 3, 1843. He was a judge of the [[Maryland Court of Appeals]] from 1851 to 1857, and afterwards a collector of customs at [[Baltimore]], Maryland, from 1857 to 1861. He moved to [[Annapolis, Maryland]], and served as [[Secretary of State of Maryland]] from 1872 until his death in 1873.
==Death and interment== Mason died on March 28, 1873 in [[Elkton, Maryland|Elkton]], Maryland at age 57.<ref name=GH/> He is interred in [[Rose Hill Cemetery (Maryland)]] in Hagerstown, Maryland.
==Marriage and children== Mason married Margaret Augusta Cowan in [[Allegheny City, Pennsylvania|Alleghany City]], Pennsylvania on December 14, 1842.<ref name=GH/> The couple had four children:<ref name=GH/>
*Louise Gilmer Mason Terry (February 12, 1844&ndash;September 26, 1921)<ref name=GH/> *William Temple Thomson Mason (December 12, 1845&ndash;April 5, 1847)<ref name=GH/> *Elizabeth Mason Porter (born March 28, 1848)<ref name=GH/> *John Thomson Mason (born January 3, 1850)<ref name=GH/>
==Relations== John Thomson Mason Jr. was a grandnephew of [[George Mason]] (1725&ndash;1792); grandson of [[Thomson Mason]] (1733&ndash;1785);<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> nephew of [[Stevens Thomson Mason (Virginia)|Stevens Thomson Mason]] (1760&ndash;1803); son of [[John Thomson Mason]] (1765&ndash;1824) and Elizabeth Beltzhoover Mason (1781&ndash;1836);<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> second cousin of [[Thomson Francis Mason]] (1785&ndash;1838);<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> first cousin of [[Armistead Thomson Mason]] (1787&ndash;1819), [[John Thomson Mason (1787–1850)|John Thomson Mason]] (1787&ndash;1850), and [[James Murray Mason]] (1798&ndash;1871);<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> and first cousin once removed of [[Stevens T. Mason|Stevens Thomson Mason]] (1811&ndash;1843).<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/>
